# Agentlab UI

This file is the durable repo backlog for `CodexAgile`.
## Workflow
- Paula Product owns backlog intake, grooming, and prioritization.
- New backlog requests and product changes should be captured here before implementation.
- Items in `Inbox` or `Grooming` are not implementation-ready.
- The markdown file remains the source of truth for backlog state.
## Status lanes

### Inbox
Use for raw ideas, requests, and unresolved feature discussions.

### Grooming
Use for items Paula is clarifying, scoping, or prioritizing.

### Ready
Use for items Paula has scoped well enough for implementation. Every `Ready` item should have `Ready for Implementation?: Yes` plus clear scope notes and acceptance criteria.

### In Progress
Use for items currently being implemented, reviewed, or deployed.

### Done
Use for completed items with outcome notes.
## BACKLOG-056 - Capture blocker reason when a ticket is marked blocked
- Status: Done
- Owner: Paula Product
- Requester: current session
- Date added: 2026-04-14
- Updated: 2026-04-14T15:11:00.000Z
- Due Date: 
- Priority: P1
- Effort: 2
- Sprint Assigned: Sprint 11
- Ready for Implementation?: Yes
- Tech handoff owner: Ben
- Summary: Open Paula chat with a blocker-reason prompt as soon as a user marks a ticket blocked so the team captures context while it is fresh.
- Outcome / user value: Users can explain why work is blocked at the moment they mark it blocked instead of leaving the team without enough context to act.
- Scope notes: In scope, triggering the existing Paula chat flow from the blocked action, carrying the blocked ticket's identity into the first prompt, and capturing the blocker reason through that chat path. In scope, letting the user dismiss the prompt without undoing the blocked state. Out of scope, making the blocker reason a required markdown field, inventing a separate modal, or redesigning blocked-state visuals already tracked elsewhere.
- Acceptance criteria:
  - [ ] When a user marks a ticket blocked, the existing Paula chat opens automatically from that action.
  - [ ] The first Paula prompt clearly asks what is blocking the selected ticket and includes enough ticket context that the user knows which ticket they are describing.
  - [ ] If the user enters a blocker reason, the response is captured through the existing Paula chat path without requiring a second manual launch.
  - [ ] If the user dismisses or ignores the prompt, the ticket remains blocked and the UI does not silently clear that state.
  - [ ] The blocked flow stays calm and lightweight, adding context capture without forcing a separate form before the status change completes.
- Dependencies: blocked-ticket interaction, Paula chat window, blocked-state action wiring.
- Links: current session request
- Implementation notes: Original intake preserved verbatim: when user marks a ticket as blocked, pop up the chat window and ask what is blocking?


## BACKLOG-064 - Preset board filters from top-header summary clicks
- Status: Done
- Owner: Paula Product
- Requester: current session
- Date added: 2026-04-14
- Updated: 2026-04-14T15:11:00.000Z
- Due Date: 
- Priority: P1
- Effort: 2
- Sprint Assigned: Sprint 11
- Ready for Implementation?: Yes
- Tech handoff owner: Ben
- Summary: Make the top-header `Open`, `Blocked`, `Done`, `Epics`, and `Unassigned` summaries clickable so each one applies the matching board filters and refreshes the kanban view.
- Outcome / user value: Users can jump directly from high-level board counts to the relevant slice of work without manually rebuilding filters every time.
- Scope notes: In scope, making the top-header summary items clickable, applying a predefined filter set for each clicked summary, refreshing the visible kanban state immediately, and emphasizing only the lanes needed for that filtered view while minimizing lanes that are not relevant. In scope, preserving any selected sprint when the preset does not need to change sprint context, except when the `Unassigned` preset needs to surface unassigned work directly. Out of scope, custom user-defined presets, changing backlog data, or redesigning the header summary labels themselves.
- Acceptance criteria:
  - [ ] Clicking `Open` applies a preset that shows non-done work and refreshes the kanban immediately.
  - [ ] Clicking `Blocked` applies a preset that shows blocked work and refreshes the kanban immediately while preserving blocked items in their lane context.
  - [ ] Clicking `Done` applies a preset that shows completed work and refreshes the kanban immediately.
  - [ ] Clicking `Epics` applies a preset that surfaces epic-oriented board context and refreshes the kanban immediately.
  - [ ] Clicking `Unassigned` applies a preset that surfaces unassigned work immediately without requiring the user to build the filter set manually.
  - [ ] After any preset is applied, lanes relevant to the resulting view are visually emphasized and lanes not needed for that view are minimized rather than competing equally for space.
  - [ ] Repeated clicks on the same header item produce a stable, predictable board view instead of accumulating conflicting filter state.
- Dependencies: top-header summary controls, board filtering model, kanban refresh behavior, lane emphasis behavior, unassigned-work filter behavior, BACKLOG-017, BACKLOG-037.
- Links: current session request
- Implementation notes: Original intake preserved in product terms: clicking on Open, Blocked, Done, Epics, and Unassigned in the top header should preset the filters, refresh the kanban, maximize the lanes that matter for that view, and minimize the lanes that do not.


## BACKLOG-065 - Include project list in saved user layout
- Status: Done
- Owner: Paula Product
- Requester: current session
- Date added: 2026-04-14
- Updated: 2026-04-14T15:11:00.000Z
- Due Date: 
- Priority: P2
- Effort: 1
- Sprint Assigned: Sprint 11
- Ready for Implementation?: Yes
- Tech handoff owner: Ben
- Summary: Extend `Save layout` so it restores the user's project list, filters, sorting, and current sprint along with the saved board layout.
- Outcome / user value: Users can return to the same working context without rebuilding their project list, board filters, sort order, or sprint focus after leaving and coming back.
- Scope notes: In scope, saving the current user's project list, active filters, current sorting, and current sprint selection as part of the existing per-user layout payload, restoring that state on the next visit, and keeping the behavior scoped to that same user only. In scope, treating this as an extension of the existing single saved layout rather than a separate saved-preferences feature. Out of scope, shared saved layouts across users, multiple named saved layouts, or changes to the backlog markdown file itself.
- Acceptance criteria:
  - [ ] Activating `Save layout` stores the current user's project list, active filters, current sorting, and current sprint together with the rest of the saved layout state.
  - [ ] When the same user returns later, the app restores the saved project list, filters, sorting, and current sprint alongside the previously saved layout settings.
  - [ ] The saved project list, filters, sorting, and sprint state remain scoped to the current user and do not overwrite another user's saved context.
  - [ ] If one or more of those saved state elements do not exist yet, the app keeps its current fallback behavior instead of failing to restore the layout.
- Dependencies: BACKLOG-003, per-user preference storage, project list persistence model, board filter persistence, sorting persistence, sprint selection persistence.
- Links: current session request
- Implementation notes: Follow-up to the shipped `Save layout` behavior so saved board context also includes the user's project list, active filters, sorting, and current sprint.


## Item template

```md## BACKLOG-XXX - Title
- Status: Inbox | Grooming | Ready | In Progress | Testing | Review | Done
- Owner: Paula Product
- Requester: Name or source thread
- Date added: YYYY-MM-DD
- Last updated: YYYY-MM-DD
- Priority: P0 | P1 | P2 | P3
- Effort: 1 | 2 | 3
- Sprint Assigned: Sprint name
- Ready for Implementation?: No | Yes
- Tech handoff owner: Unassigned | Ben | Tess | Dave
- Tess sign-off: No
- Paula sign-off: No
- Summary: One-sentence description of the request
- Outcome / user value: Why this matters
- Scope notes: In scope / out of scope / open questions
- Acceptance criteria:
  - [ ] Specific observable outcome
- Dependencies: Systems, approvals, or blocking tickets
- Links: Issue, PR, docs, chat thread, artifacts
- Implementation notes: Implemented Auto Sprint selection and apply flow in the app, with dependency-aware filtering and automatic sprint assignment.
```

