- Summary: Let multiple authenticated users use the same hosted server concurrently without leaking each other's files, layouts, or in-progress actions.
- Outcome / user value: Teams can share one hosted deployment safely instead of needing a separate server per person to avoid collisions and lost context.
- Scope notes: In scope, defining the isolation rules needed for concurrent hosted use across uploaded backlog files, saved layouts, Paula sessions, and sprint-run actions on one server. In scope, clarifying what is user-scoped, what is project-scoped, and what conflict handling is required when more than one user touches the same hosted backlog. In scope, preserving the markdown file as the source of truth while making concurrent usage legible and safe. Out of scope, fine-grained enterprise permissions, billing, or a full collaborative presence system.
- Acceptance criteria:
  - [ ] Multiple authenticated users can use the same hosted server without seeing another user's private saved layout or profile-scoped project context by default.
  - [ ] The story defines whether uploaded backlog files are private per user, shared per project, or shared per workspace, and how that scope is surfaced in the UI.
  - [ ] The story defines how Paula sessions and sprint-run actions are isolated or labeled when more than one user is active at the same time.
  - [ ] The story defines the minimum conflict-handling behavior when two users try to update the same hosted markdown backlog close together.
  - [ ] The concurrent-use design preserves the markdown backlog as the durable source of truth rather than introducing hidden story state that can diverge.
- Dependencies: BACKLOG-045, BACKLOG-068, BACKLOG-070, write-safety model, hosted session isolation decision.
- Links: current session request
- Implementation notes: Original intake preserved in product terms: after hosted auth exists, allow concurrent usage by multiple users from the same server.

