## BACKLOG-029 - Prevent seven-lane board squashing on narrower screens
- Status: Done
- Owner: Paula Product
- Requester: current session
- Date added: 2026-04-13
- Updated: 2026-04-13T22:13:52Z
- Due Date: 
- Priority: P1
- Effort: 2
- Sprint Assigned: Sprint 2
- Ready for Implementation?: Yes
- Tech handoff owner: Ben
- Summary: Keep the board readable after adding `Testing` and `Review` by switching to horizontal overflow with minimum lane widths instead of squeezing all seven lanes to fit.
- Outcome / user value: Users on narrower screens can still read cards and understand lane boundaries without the board collapsing into cramped, low-signal columns.
- Scope notes: In scope, a responsive board treatment that preserves all seven lanes, uses a minimum readable lane width, and allows horizontal scrolling when the viewport cannot fit every lane comfortably. Out of scope, hiding lanes, merging states on small screens, or changing story content density beyond what is needed to preserve readability.
- Acceptance criteria:
  - [ ] All seven lanes remain visible in the board model.
  - [ ] Narrow viewports use horizontal overflow instead of compressing lanes below a readable width.
  - [ ] Lane cards stay legible and lane boundaries remain clear on smaller screens.
  - [ ] No lane is hidden or merged to make the layout fit.
- Dependencies: board lane layout, lane width rules, viewport-responsive behavior, BACKLOG-028.
- Links: current session request
- Implementation notes: Implemented the seven-lane board grid with horizontal overflow and minimum lane widths so narrow screens scroll instead of crushing columns.

